original_title: Brooklyn: New Dock Street - Water Street
text:
New Dock Street, west side, north of Water Street, showing part of the dump yard which the W. P. A. later developed into a storage yard for the Department of Purchase of the City of New York and erected a new storehouse, known as the Brooklyn Bridge storehouse. The two-story building is an old stable; it appears in Robinson's 1886 atlas.

Late 1935

text:
New Dock Street, west side, north of Water Street, showing part of the site which the W. P. A. later developed into a storage yard for the New York City Department of Purchase and where a new storehouse was erected. On the right is an old stable; it appears on Robinson's 1886 map. The Manhattan Bridge appears in the background.

The storehouse is being built for the Department of Purchase of the City of New York, directly under the bridge on the East River shore. New Dock Street is on the right, where the Sanitation Department trucks are parked and in the background is the Manhattan shore and the Manhattan Bridge.

original_title: Brooklyn: New Dock Street - Water Street
text:

A. is conducting operations in the erection of a new storehouse--known as the Brooklyn Bridge storehouse--for the New York City Department of Purchase, near the Brooklyn Bridge anchorage. original_title: Brooklyn: New Dock Street - Water Street
text:
New Dock Street, west side, north of Water Street, showing W. P. A. construction work on a new storage yard and storehouse (left) for the New York City Department of Purchase under the Brooklyn Bridge on the East River shore. In the background is the structure which, when completed, will support the permanent hoppers for sand and gravel. Across the river is the Manhattan shoreline.

December 7, 1936

Works Progress Administration
Project 65-97-68

original_title: Brooklyn: New Dock Street - Water Street
text:
New Dock Street, west side, north of Water Street, showing the northeast end of the yard which the W. P. A. is building for the Department of Purchase of the City of New York as part of the Brooklyn Bridge storehouse project under the Brooklyn Bridge. The broken concrete was very difficult to break up owing to the fact that old boiler tubes were used in place of reinforcing steel. Several nests of this pipe can be seen on the right. The thoroughfare seen is New Dock Street.

December 7, 1936

Works Progress Administration
Project 65-97-68

original_title: Brooklyn: New Dock Street - Water Street
text:
New Dock Street, west side, north of Water Street, showing the east side of the job-location yard of the W. P. A. Brooklyn Bridge storehouse project. The storehouse, partly seen on the right, was erected for the New York City Department of Purchase. In the right foreground are men laying in concrete; in the center is the broken concrete foundation which had to be excavated down to the proper grade line. The automobiles are parked on New Dock Street.

December 7, 1936

Works Progress Administration
Project 65-97-68
